    <section data-section-key="belege">
      <h2>Don't take my word for it, try it</h2>
      <p class="lead">No screenshots, no promises: real, running software with open source. The credentials are right on each login page, all data is made up.</p>
      <ul class="facts">
        <li><strong>FlowGate</strong>, multi-stage request &amp; approval workflow with roles, an enforced state machine and a real-time board (Angular, NestJS, PostgreSQL, WebSocket). <a href="https://flowgate.kozlowski-it.de" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open demo</a> · <a href="https://github.com/Kozlowski-IT/flowgate" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></li>
        <li><strong>Quellwerk</strong>, ask documents in plain language instead of searching; the search runs entirely locally, an AI answer is optional (Python, FastAPI, RAG/embeddings). <a href="https://quellwerk.kozlowski-it.de" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open demo</a> · <a href="https://github.com/Kozlowski-IT/quellwerk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></li>
        <li><strong>SaaS backend architecture</strong>, multi-tenant backend with row-level security, domain-driven design and an event architecture; shows how to separate multiple clients safely on one platform. <a href="/assets/docs/saas-architektur-de.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Architecture study (PDF)</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section data-section-key="ki">
      <h2>And the AI question</h2>
      <p class="lead">Yes, I use AI as a tool, the way a carpenter reaches for a machine instead of a hand plane. It takes the routine off my plate and makes me faster. But the decisions (how something is built, what's secure, what fits your workflow) and the responsibility for them stay with me. <strong>Your data does not go into any AI</strong>. The tool helps me with code, not with your content. And AI is not a button that spits out finished software: demanding projects still take real time and care.</p>
    </section>

